<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-12-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-12-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="8" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d8">
                    <head>No. 8.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Tree</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-12-19"><hi rend="italic">December</hi> 19,
                            1885</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 17.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch, No. 20, of the 24th ultimo,
                        inclosing specimens of postal cards and international letter stamps adopted
                        by the Independent Free State of the Congo, and informing me that you had
                        been officially notified that the postal service of that State would be in
                        operation on the 1st of January next, has been received.</p>
                    <p>In reply I have to inform you that I have communicated the contents of your
                        dispatch to the Postmaster-General.</p>
                    <p>I am, sir, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>T. F. BAYARD.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>